# physics.bld - BLD for Physics
#
# Status: MIXED (Thermo/Circuits VALIDATED, others EXPLORATORY)
#
# Core Insight: Physics IS a traverser. Physical laws define structural constraints.
# When any structure aligns with physics, alignment cost IS physical energy.

structure PhysicsBLD

# =============================================================================
# DIMENSIONS (D) - What repeats
# =============================================================================

D particles: N [parallel]
D spatial: 3 [parallel]             # 3D space
D temporal: 1 [sequential]          # Time
D qubits: Q [parallel]              # Quantum systems: Hilbert dim = 2^Q
D lattice: L [parallel]             # System size

# =============================================================================
# BOUNDARIES (B) - Where behavior partitions
# =============================================================================

# Rule 1: B = Topological (Invariant Under D)
# X(D) = X(D') for all D, D' → X is B

B phase: solid | liquid | gas | plasma
  solid -> ordered, low_entropy
  liquid -> disordered, medium_entropy
  gas -> maximally_disordered, high_entropy
  plasma -> ionized

B critical: subcritical | critical | supercritical
  subcritical -> finite_correlation_length
  critical -> divergent_correlation, scale_invariance
  supercritical -> continuous

B quantum_state: superposition | collapsed
  superposition -> coherent
  collapsed -> measured, classical

# Invariant thresholds (do not scale with D)
# V_th, c, T_c, Re_c, σ

# =============================================================================
# LINKS (L) - What connects to what
# =============================================================================

# Rule 2: L = Geometric (Scales with D)
# X(αD) = α^k × X(D) for some k > 0 → X is L

L coupling: particle_i -> particle_j (force=F, constant=α)
L field: source -> field_point (potential=A_μ, energy=U)
L correlation: region_a -> region_b (fisher_metric=g, length=ξ)
L entanglement: qubit_a -> qubit_b (entropy=S_A)

# Scaling examples: C ~ n, U ~ V, S ~ n

# =============================================================================
# THE MAPPING RULES
# =============================================================================
#
# Rule 1: B = Topological
#   Observable X is B if X(D) = X(D') for all D
#   Examples: V_th, c, T_c, Re_c, σ
#
# Rule 2: L = Geometric
#   Observable X is L if X(αD) = α^k × X(D)
#   Examples: Capacitance, field energy, entanglement entropy
#
# Rule 3: D = Repetition Count
#   Observable X is D if X = integer count of homogeneous elements
#   Examples: Particle number N, spatial dim d, qubit count

# =============================================================================
# DOMAIN STATUS
# =============================================================================
#
# | Domain           | Status      | Key Validations               |
# |------------------|-------------|-------------------------------|
# | Thermodynamics   | VALIDATED   | 10/10 tests, Second Law       |
# | Circuits         | VALIDATED   | R² = 1.0 for D×L scaling      |
# | Electromagnetism | EXPLORATORY | U(1) gauge reframed           |
# | Quantum          | EXPLORATORY | B = measurement, L = entangle |
# | Fluids           | EXPLORATORY | Re as B, viscosity as L       |
# | Phase Transitions| EXPLORATORY | Critical phenomena as B       |

# =============================================================================
# D×L SCALING IN PHYSICS
# =============================================================================
#
# The principle: D multiplies L, not B
#
# | System           | D         | L              | B (invariant)    |
# |------------------|-----------|----------------|------------------|
# | Capacitor array  | N devices | C_single       | V_breakdown      |
# | Magnetic material| N atoms   | Magnetization  | T_Curie          |
# | Quantum system   | N qubits  | Entanglement   | Measurement rule |
# | Fluid pipe       | Length L  | Viscous flow   | Re_critical      |
#
# Cost formula: Physical energy = B_cost + D × L_cost

# =============================================================================
# COMPENSATION IN PHYSICS
# =============================================================================
#
# L → B Compensation:
#   | System         | Mechanism     | Effect              |
#   |----------------|---------------|---------------------|
#   | Antenna array  | N elements    | Beam steering       |
#   | Neural network | Cascaded      | Sharp classification|
#   | Error correct  | Entangled     | Fault tolerance     |
#
# B Cannot Compensate for L:
#   Circuit without feedback → can't stabilize
#   Shielding without coupling → blocks all signals
#   Measurement without entanglement → no quantum advantage

# =============================================================================
# INTENSIVE VS EXTENSIVE
# =============================================================================
#
# | Property Type              | BLD | Examples                    |
# |----------------------------|-----|-----------------------------|
# | Intensive (size-independent)| B   | Temperature, pressure       |
# | Extensive (scales with size)| L/D | Energy, volume, entropy     |

# =============================================================================
# FALSIFICATION TESTS
# =============================================================================
#
# Any physics BLD mapping should pass:
#   1. B invariance: X(D) = X(D') for all system sizes
#   2. L scaling: X(αD) = α^k × X(D) for k > 0
#   3. Cost decomposition: Total = B + D×L with independent measurements
#   4. Compensation asymmetry: L→B works, B→L fails
#
# If any test fails, revise the mapping.

returns: PhysicsAnalysis
